Factual Audiovisual Narratives on YouTube -- tTracing Televised ‘Truth’: Reality Effect and Unreliable Narration in TV News -- tInterdisciplinary Perspectives On (Un)Reliability -- t(Un)reliable Narration in Journalism: The Fine Line between Fact and Fiction -- tUnreliable Narratives in the US Elections: How Much Reliability Can a Campaign Take? -- tUnreliable Narration in Law Courts -- tUnreliable Narration in Historical Studies -- tUnreliability in Patient Narratives: From Clinical Assessment to Narrative Practice -- tCommunicating Dreams: On the Struggle for Reliable Dream Reporting and the Unreliability of Dream Reports -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThough the phenomenon known as “unreliable narration” or “narrative unreliability” has received a lot of attention during the last two decades, narratological research has mainly focused on its manifestations in narrative fiction, particularly in homodiegetic or first-person narration. Except for film, forms and functions of unreliable narration in other genres, media and disciplines have so far been relatively neglected. The present volume redresses the balance by directing scholarly attention to disciplines and domains that narratology has so far largely ignored. It aims at initiating an interdisciplinary approach to, and debate on, narrative unreliability, exploring unreliable narration in a broad range of literary genres, other media and non-fictional text-types, contexts and disciplines beyond literary studies. Crossing the boundaries between genres, media, and disciplines, the volume acknowledges that the question of whether or not to believe or trust a narrator transcends the field of literature: The issues of (un)reliability and (un)trustworthiness play a crucial role in many areas of human life as well as a wide spectrum of academic fields ranging from law to history, and from psychology to the study of culture.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aUnreliable narration.  aintermedial/transgeneric narratology.1 aAltes, Liesbeth Korthals, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArnauld, Andreas Von, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBietz, Christoph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoothe, Brigitte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrütsch, Matthias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDernbach, Beatrice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElter, Andreas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHühn, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJaeger, Stephan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuhn, Markus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMargolin, Uri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartens, Gunther, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartini, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMildorf, Jarmila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNünning, Ansgar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNünning, Vera, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNünning, Vera, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPettersson, Bo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchwanecke, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStojković, Dragica, econtributo